Model 1¶

First we will experiment with a new, slightly more complex net. In the figure below, the dark part of the lines represent "to" pathways and the red nodes are the initial attackers. See the table below for the rates.

Use the SFT API to create and draw a net¶

In [121]: 
A = SFT('A', ['normal' , 'infected'], ['B', 'F'], 
    {'B': np.array([[.5, 0], [.5,.01]]), 'F' : np.array([[.5, 0], [.5, .01]])},
    ['clean', 'malicious'], 'external')
# Node A sends messages to B and F

B = SFT('B', ['normal' , 'infected'], ['A', 'D', 'F'], 
    {'A': np.array([[.5, 0], [.5,.01]]), 'D': np.array([[.5,0], [.5, .01]]), 'F' : np.array([[.5, 0], [.5, .01]])},
    ['clean', 'malicious'], 'internal')
# B sends messages to A, D and F
C = SFT('C', ['normal' , 'infected'], ['A', 'B', 'F'],
    {'A': np.array([[.5, 0], [.5,.01]]), 'B': np.array([[.5, 0], [.5, .01]]), 'F' : np.array([[.5, 0], [.5, .01]])},
    ['clean', 'malicious'], 'internal')
# C sends messages to A, B and F


D = SFT('D', ['normal' , 'infected'], ['A', 'C', 'F'], 
    {'A': np.array([[.5, 0], [.5,.01]]), 'C': np.array([[.5,0], [.5, .01]]), 'F' : np.array([[.24, 0], [.24, .01]])},
    ['clean', 'malicious'], 'internal')
# D sends nodes to A, C and F

E = SFT('E', ['normal' , 'infected'], ['A', 'B', 'C', 'F'], 
    {'A': np.array([[.5, 0], [.5,.01]]), 'B': np.array([[.5,0], [.5, .01]]), 
     'C': np.array([[.5,0], [.5, .01]]), 'F' : np.array([[.5, 0], [.5, .01]])},
    ['clean', 'malicious'], 'internal')
# E (slowly) sends nodes to A, B, C and F

F = SFT('F', ['normal' , 'infected'], ['A', 'E'], 
    {'A': np.array([[.5, 0], [.5,.01]]), 'E' : np.array([[.5, 0], [.5, .01]])},
    ['clean', 'malicious'], 'external')
# F sends nodes to A and E




nodes = [A,B,C,D,E,F]
net = SFTNet(nodes)

Draw the ROC curve in parallel.¶

In the example below, there are 1600 datasets of each type (with attacker, without attacker). See the ROC plot below the code.

In [*]: 
s0 = {'A': 'infected', 'B': 'normal', 'C': 'normal', 'D': 'normal', 'E': 'normal', 'F': 'infected'}

# Change params of this on a case by case basis #######
percore = 200
def f1(x):
    return get_roc_coords(x, percore, percore, net, s0={'A': 'infected', 'B': 'normal', 'C': 'normal', \
                                                        'D': 'normal', 'E': 'normal', 'F': 'infected'} , \
                                  T=3000, uni_samp_size=1000, mcmc_steps=500000, printsteps=False)
#######################################################

from multiprocessing import Pool
p = Pool(8)

result_1 =p.map(f1, [1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8])

Plot the results¶

So what is happening here. Let's take a look at the likelihood ratios and the probability of the data without an attacker.

In [8]: 
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2)
a1= ax1.hist(pos[:,0] - pos[:,1], label='LLR with an attacker', color='b')
a2= ax1.hist(neg[:,0] -  neg[:,1], label='LLR without an attacker', color='r', alpha=.7)
ax1.set_title('LLR as if there is an attacker')
#plt.legend()
ax1.legend(loc = 'lower center', bbox_to_anchor = (.5, -.35))
a3= ax2.hist(pos[:,1], label = 'with attacker', alpha=.5, color= 'r', bins=np.arange(-100, -85,2))
a4= ax2.hist(neg[:,1], label = 'without attacker', alpha=.7, bins=np.arange(-100, -80,1))
ax2.set_title('P(data | no attacler) under both scenarios')
ax2.legend(loc = 'lower center', bbox_to_anchor = (.5, -.35))
fig.set_size_inches(16,4)

The ROC curve shows that our likelihood ratio performs better than the anomaly detector. Also, the figure above shows the distribution of the LLR when there is and when there isn't an attacker (left plot) as well as the anomaly detector when there is and when there isn't an attacker (right plot). There seems to be more separation with our likelihood ratio, which is a good sign.

Note that without an attacker, the log likelihood stays essentially at 0. Furthermore, the bar of low log-likelihood ratios can be due to the cases when no nodes get infected by T. One way to fix this would be to extend T. However, this will just increase the accuracy of both methods. We need to find a way to separate the two. Let's use a version of Brian's nets when T goes to 20000 but the rate of infected transmission is .01.

Let's try and see the exact relationship between \(P(\text { data } | \text{ attacker })\) and the simply anomaly detector...

In [139]: 
import statsmodels.api as sm
w_attacker = sm.OLS(pos[:,0], sm.tools.add_constant(pos[:,1]))
w_attacker_fitted = w_attacker.fit()
print 'The OLS parameters are', '\n', 'constant = ' , w_attacker_fitted.params[0], '\n', 
print 'slope = ' , w_attacker_fitted.params[1]
print 'R2 = ' , w_attacker_fitted.rsquared

The OLS parameters are 
constant =  -5.20214398555 
slope =  0.960015361466
R2 =  0.993157819721

We see that when regressing \(P( \text{ data } | \text{ attacker })\) on a constant and \(P(\text{ data } | \text{ no attacker })\) , the coefficient on the regressor is \(.96\). This signals that \(P( \text{ data } | \text{ attacker })\) moves almost one-to-one with \(P( \text{ data } | \text{ no attacker } )\). More importantly, and \(R^2\) of .99 says that almost all of the variation in our likelihood is simply due to variation in the no attacker likelihood (more on why below). The plot on the left shows that our likelihood ratio only begins to separate itself from the simple anomaly detector when the simple anomaly detector has a low probability. The question becomes, why does this relationship hold in this net configuration (and not the one above)?

One possibility is that \(T\) is too low. Let's see what happend when we raise \(T\) to \(30000.\)

In this case, both methods do slightly better but there is almost no separation. Omitting plots, the scatter plots are similar to the case when \(T= 20000\) . So why does this happen? The key is to note that when performing uniform importance sampling, we sample all possible infection orderings, including the ordering when no nodes get infected. However, \(P (\text { data } | \text{ no nodes infected, attacker exists})\) is essentially the same as \(P( \text { data } | \text { no attacker })\) (the only difference would come from the slight increase in firing rate from the node that was originally infected at \(t=0\).) Taking that into account, if our likelihood places a relatively high weight on the "infection ordering" where no nodes get infected, then the value of the likelihood will correspond almost 1-1 with \(P ( \text { data } | \text{ no attacker } )\). In other words, changes in \(P(\text{ data } | \text { no attacker} )\) will correspond to a proportional change in\(P(\text{ data } | \text { attacker} )\) and the likelihood ratio will not change.

To check this hypotheses, one way to shift the weight of the likelihood away from the case where no nodes get infected is to increase the attackers malicious attacking rate. In the following example, I increase it from \(1/10000\) to \(1/2000\). In the simulation there are 400 data sets of each type. I run through 3 examples and provide brief discussion at the end.

In all of the cases when \(A\) fires faster, our method clearly does better and this is evident in all plots. The ROC curves show that our ROC dominates the anomaly detector. The histograms show a greater separation of the with and withouth attacker case for the likelihood ratio and the scatter plots show that our likelihood ratio is picking up on variations in the data that are not due to the case where no nodes get infected. Or in other words, the right scatter plot shows that there is variation in \(P( \text {data } | \text{ attacker } )\) that is not due to variation in \(P( \text { data } | \text{ no attacker } )\)
